docs.abstract: Mike Isaac, a tech reporter for The Times, now uses Uber and Lyft infrequently, though he remains a steady user of Twitter and HQ Trivia.
docs.snippet: Mike Isaac, a tech reporter for The Times, now uses Uber and Lyft infrequently, though he remains a steady user of Twitter and HQ Trivia.
docs.lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? Mike Isaac, a technology reporter for The Times based in San Francisco, discussed the tech he’s using.

headline.main: He Weaned Himself From Ride-Hailing Apps. Here’s Why.
headline.print_headline: Covering Uber and Lyft, but Trying Not to Use Them

docs.abstract: The trade pact’s future hangs in the balance. As negotiations begin this week, so do the futures of many products that we think of as quintessentially American.
docs.snippet: The trade pact’s future hangs in the balance. As negotiations begin this week, so do the futures of many products that we think of as quintessentially American.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The North American Free Trade Agreement may not be a topic of frequent discussion in your household, but the trade pact probably plays a big role in your daily life.

headline.main: These 3 Everyday Products Show Who Won and Lost From Nafta

docs.abstract: Ford is phasing out its passenger cars, except one: the Mustang. The car may be only modestly profitable for Ford, but it has deep emotional power.
docs.snippet: Ford is phasing out its passenger cars, except one: the Mustang. The car may be only modestly profitable for Ford, but it has deep emotional power.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Ford Motor all but eliminated passenger cars from its North American lineup earlier this month to concentrate on trucks and S.U.V.s, it turned the page on a long and storied history of now-defunct but once red-hot nameplates: the Model T, the Model A, the Galaxie, the Fairlane, the Thunderbird and the Falcon, to name several.

headline.main: ‘Mustang Means Freedom’: Why Ford Is Saving an American Icon
headline.print_headline: Saving an American Icon: ‘Mustang Means Freedom’

docs.abstract: The rise of passive investing over the past decade fueled the stock market’s historic boom. Now it’s acting as an accelerant as markets decline.
docs.snippet: The rise of passive investing over the past decade fueled the stock market’s historic boom. Now it’s acting as an accelerant as markets decline.
docs.lead_paragraph: A decade ago, the center of gravity on Wall Street were raucous trading desks and stock exchange floors. These days, the locus has shifted to far quieter places, where computers are in charge.

headline.main: One Cause of Market Turbulence: Computer-Driven Index Funds
headline.print_headline: Quiet Player In Volatility Of Market: Computers

docs.abstract: Chuck Plunkett, who wrote an editorial last month that called the newspaper’s hedge fund owners “vulture capitalists,” said he resigned after another critical editorial he wrote was not allowed to run.
docs.snippet: Chuck Plunkett, who wrote an editorial last month that called the newspaper’s hedge fund owners “vulture capitalists,” said he resigned after another critical editorial he wrote was not allowed to run.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOULDER, Colo. — Chuck Plunkett said he knew that he was risking his job as the editorial page editor of The Denver Post when he wrote an impassioned editorial last month blasting the newspaper’s hedge-fund owners as “vulture capitalists” who had hobbled Colorado’s largest newspaper with deep layoffs and cost-cutting.

headline.main: Denver Post Editor Who Criticized Paper’s Ownership Resigns
headline.print_headline: Denver Post Editor Who Criticized ‘Vulture’ Owners Resigns After Column Is Blocked

docs.abstract: To create a Super Bowl snack, we bought the same ingredients at a new Whole Foods 365 store and a Walmart. The prices were different. So were the outcomes.
docs.snippet: To create a Super Bowl snack, we bought the same ingredients at a new Whole Foods 365 store and a Walmart. The prices were different. So were the outcomes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon and Walmart are battling to dominate the grocery market, fueling a price war that could rearrange where America shops for food.

headline.print_headline: Testing Amazon Effect With a Super Bowl Snack: Cheesy Meatballs

byline.original: By Michael Corkery and Zach Wichter

docs.abstract: As part of an effort to stay connected with people in the digital age, Mattel is sponsoring a nationwide search for a custom vehicle that can be a model for a 50th anniversary Hot Wheels car.
docs.snippet: As part of an effort to stay connected with people in the digital age, Mattel is sponsoring a nationwide search for a custom vehicle that can be a model for a 50th anniversary Hot Wheels car.
docs.lead_paragraph: After six billion vehicles sold, Hot Wheels is looking for one more car to race down those plastic orange tracks. And it could be yours.

headline.main: Hot Wheels Hits the Road to Reach Its Fans
headline.print_headline: Racing to Stay Relevant, Hot Wheels Begins a Quest for the Best Custom Car

docs.abstract: More buyers are ticking the sunroof option box, and carmakers in search of an open-air feeling are making them bigger. Safety advocates see a problem.
docs.snippet: More buyers are ticking the sunroof option box, and carmakers in search of an open-air feeling are making them bigger. Safety advocates see a problem.
docs.lead_paragraph: After 18-year-old Liza Hankins was thrown through the closed sunroof of her sport-utility vehicle during a crash and paralyzed, her family sued the truck’s maker, claiming it had failed to live up to its safety responsibilities.

headline.main: Sunroofs Are Growing in Size and Popularity. Rules Haven’t Kept Up.
headline.print_headline: Sunroofs Expand, But Safety Rules Haven’t Kept Up

docs.abstract: Lord & Taylor is partnering with Walmart to start a “premium” fashion store on Walmart.com, a move reflecting the challenges of modern retailing.
docs.snippet: Lord & Taylor is partnering with Walmart to start a “premium” fashion store on Walmart.com, a move reflecting the challenges of modern retailing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Lord & Taylor, the once leading fashion retailer that has been fading, considers itself a trailblazer. It was one of the first major retailers to install an elevator in its store and was one of the first to hire a woman as president.

headline.main: Walmart Goes Upscale, Offering Lord & Taylor Brands
headline.print_headline: Another First for Lord & Taylor: An Online Pairing With Walmart

docs.abstract: President Trump’s decision to place a tariff on aluminum has the beer industry angry over higher costs. How would the price of beer be affected?
docs.snippet: President Trump’s decision to place a tariff on aluminum has the beer industry angry over higher costs. How would the price of beer be affected?
docs.lead_paragraph: As President Trump announced sweeping trade tariffs on imported steel and aluminum, raising the specter of a possible trade war, one question has repeatedly come up: Will Americans drink less beer?

headline.main: Will Trump’s Trade Policy Fit Into a Can of Beer?
headline.print_headline: A ‘Beer Tax’?  Metal Tariffs  Will Ripple,  Brewers Say
